              <fr:month>2</fr:month>
              <fr:day>11</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:addr>jms-017L</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-017L.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="deterministic finite automaton">deterministic finite automaton</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>A <html:em><html:strong>deterministic finite automaton</html:strong></html:em> or <html:em><html:strong>DFA</html:strong></html:em> for short is an <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-017H.xml" title="non-deterministic finite automaton" addr="jms-017H" type="local">NFA</fr:link> for which the transition relation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Delta \colon  Q\times  \Sigma \mathbin {\nrightarrow } Q]]></fr:tex> is a <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00KF.xml" title="function" addr="jms-00KF" type="local">function</fr:link>, i.e. a <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00KF.xml" title="function" addr="jms-00KF" type="local">total</fr:link> and <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00K7.xml" title="partial function" addr="jms-00K7" type="local">functional</fr:link> relation. This states, in other words, that to each state each state <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q\in  Q]]></fr:tex> can transition along each symbol <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\in \Sigma ]]></fr:tex> to one and only one state, which we conventionally write <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\delta {\mathopen {}\left (q,a\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>. Indeed, we will often write <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M = (Q,\Sigma ,\delta ,s,F)]]></fr:tex> for a DFA. In this case, we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q \mathrel {\xrightarrow {a}}q']]></fr:tex> if and only if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\delta {\mathopen {}\left (q,a\right )\mathclose {}}=q']]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>2</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>11</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:addr>jms-017M</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-017M.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="deterministic finite automaton › non-exclusive privatives in mathematical English"><fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-017L.xml" title="deterministic finite automaton" addr="jms-017L" type="local">deterministic finite automaton</fr:link> › non-exclusive privatives in mathematical English</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Aside</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>As an aside, it might feel strange to speak of “deterministic non-deterministic finite automata”. This is OK but can take some getting used to: mathematicians have discovered over the past several centuries that it is better for negations in terminology to mean “not necessarily” rather than “definitely not”; this is similar to the way that mathematicians often say “greater than” to mean “greater than or equal to”, reserving “strictly greater than” for the notion that excludes equality.</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
